# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dakota-territory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:dakota-territory/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:dakota-territory/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:dakota-territory/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The **Black Hills Flood of 1972**, also known as the **Rapid City Flood**, was the most detrimental flood in South Dakota history, and one of the deadliest floods in U.S. history.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The flood took place on June 9–10, 1972 in the Black Hills of Western South Dakota.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Rapid Creek and other waterways overflowed due to 15 inches (380 mm) of rain in a small area over the Black Hills.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Severe flooding of residential and commercial properties in Rapid City occurred when Canyon Lake Dam became clogged with debris and failed in the late evening hours of June 9 resulting in 238 deaths and 3,057 injuries.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Over 1,335 homes and 5,000 automobiles were destroyed.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The value of property damage was estimated to be over US$160 million in 1972 dollars ($1.23 billion in 2025 dollars).
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Flooding also occurred in Battle, Spring, Bear Butte, and Boxelder creeks.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Additionally, "a strong low-level easterly flow which forced the moist unstable air up-slope on the hills.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] This sustained orographic effect helped the air to rise, cool, and release its moisture in repeating thunderstorms.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] According to Herbert Thompson the air pattern causing this storm was noticed in big measure over the Great Plains, with a minor scale to the east of the Rockies.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] There were only what appeared to be light winds, so nothing indicated that there was a huge storm underway.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Thompson further indicates that a cold high pressure region was pushed from Canada into the Great Lakes region leading into the western part of South Dakota.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] A "mesoscale cloud mass" from Colorado also moved towards Rapid City.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] One of the cloud masses amplified the "mid-level moisture over Rapid City," while the other mass caused the pressure to stay, as the high pressure pushed downward, thus creating the right conditions to produce rainfall.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The rainfall from the upper "cloud mass" above the Black Hills formed into new smaller masses downwind which reprocessed the rain allowing for the constant rainfall.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The storm was described by Nair, Hjelmfelt, and Pielke as "convective cells of high precipitation efficiency: a characteristic of tropical precipitation systems.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Cloud seeding experiments being conducted by the Institute of Atmospheric Sciences on clouds west of Rapid City were speculated to have contributed to the unusual amount of rain.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] However, there is no evidence that the two phenomena were related.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The immense precipitation was based over the "Rapid, Boxelder, Spring, and Battle Creeks," creating run-off, along these creeks which led to flooding throughout the surrounding areas.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The intense rain began on the afternoon of June 9 and continued until after midnight on June 10.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The immense amount of rain the Black Hills received during the thunderstorms ranged from 4 to 15 inches, causing Rapid Creek and surrounding creeks to overflow and creating massive amounts of runoff that resulted in flood waters.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The run-off carried rubble to the Canyon Lake Dam creating a barrier in front of its spillway.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] This resulted in the "increase in depth of water behind the dam of 11 to 12 feet," which caused the release of more water adding to the already moving floodwaters.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The flash flood hit Rapid City the hardest around midnight on June 9; the flood waters also hit the small town of Keystone nearby.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The flood caused a tremendous amount of damage.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Flood waters displaced large rocks, trees, trailers, and vehicles, and carried homes away.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] In Rapid City the flood resulted in the deaths of "238 including 5 missing," 14 of the deaths were trained professionals.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The flood resulted in over 3,000 people being injured.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] A total of 1,335 homes were ruined, and 2,820 homes were damaged.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] More than 200 businesses were ruined, and around 5,000 cars were demolished.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The damage in Rapid City totaled $66 million in 1972 dollar value.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] As for Keystone, "eight people were killed and much of the town was washed away." The damage in Keystone totaled around $1.5 million.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The total cost of the 1972 Black Hills flood totaled $165 million, including infrastructure and utilities.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The National Weather Service Office (NWS) in Rapid City in 1972 was taking hourly surface observations, issuing local storm warnings and providing local forecasts to the media.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The personnel in Rapid City were not properly trained to make forecasts or use the technologies available to them.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] They lacked access to vital weather information to warn the area citizens.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The Rapid City National Weather Service is now a forecast office with a full-time staff of meteorologists who issue both forecasts and warnings for northeastern Wyoming and the western third of South Dakota.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] In 1972, the National Weather Service office in Rapid City did not have a teletype system to broadcast warnings.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] They instead used a one-way telephone hotline to the media to broadcast the warnings.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Today warnings are sent to a regional site where they are sent to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Weather Wire System satellite.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] NWS forecasters use the state radio system to notify 9-1-1 dispatchers and emergency personnel.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] This warning is also passed on to the Emergency Alert System (EAS).
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] In the aftermath of the 1972 flood, short-term and long-term programs were put into effect.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Many businesses were permitted to stay in the flood plain, but houses and motels were either raised or moved due to the likelihood that a flood would occur while a person may be sleeping.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The majority of the flood plain was made into large parks, which have increased in number and have been improved and updated on a continuing basis.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Canyon Lake Dam and most bridges were redesigned to prevent debris clogs during flooding.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Victims lost precious memories as stated in the Rapid City newspaper.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Flood disaster victims advised on tax breaks." Eldon L.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Smith, a South Dakota state senator, was a victim of the flood.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] The flood also killed and displaced a disproportionate number of Native people living in Rapid City.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] In 2012 the 40 year anniversary of the fateful flood occurred.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Survivors remarked on the horrific events.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Rita, who was 20 at the time, described the scene, "There was so many [people] in trees and screaming and crying and the sparks were flying from electric wires, houses were on fire, it was just — it was hell," she says.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Rita was seven months pregnant at the time of the tragedy.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] She describes her fears as, "I wouldn't wish that upon nobody," she says.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] "That's a nightmare and a half to think that you're going to die in water and your mom is gonna go with you and you're trying to do your best to keep your mom alive." Rita and her mother were swept against a building and rescued.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] There were others with the same experience while others were worse.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] Good Samaritans like Alex were left to clean up the mess and search for the less fortunate.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] He describes a gruesome scene, "I found a boy about 5 years old," Alex says.
[src:dakota-territory/1972-black-hills-flood] I didn't touch him or nothing, I just went back and told the authorities where he was at.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The **Jasper Fire** was a wildfire that occurred between August 24 and September 25, 2000, in the Black Hills of South Dakota, United States.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Burning a total of 83,508 acres (33,794 ha; 337.94 km2) across the southern hills, it is the largest wildfire in both state and Black Hills history.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] It burned over 90% of the total land area of Jewel Cave National Monument.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] As of 2024, efforts to replenish the natural vegetation inside the burn scar are still ongoing.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The cause of the fire was later determined to be arson.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Janice Stevenson of Newcastle, Wyoming, was arrested and accused of setting the fire by way of dropping a lit match and failing to put it out.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] In 2001, Stevenson pled guilty to second-degree arson and was sentenced to 25 years in prison.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] On August 24, 2000, a motorist, later identified as Janice Stevenson of Newcastle, Wyoming, stopped to use the bathroom on the side of U.S.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Highway 16 near Jasper Cave Road, just west of Jewel Cave.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] She lit a cigarette and threw the lit match on the ground, which ignited the grass.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Reportedly, Stevenson noticed the fire and drove away.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The fire was reported at 2:18 p.m. the same day.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Hot and dry conditions, low humidity, and heavy ground litter allowed the fire to spread rapidly, and shifting winds spread the fire in multiple directions.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] At its peak, the fire burned 100 acres (40 ha) per minute.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Over 1,100 firefighters were involved in fighting the blaze.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The fire was declared contained on September 8 at 6:00 p.m. and was officially deemed controlled on September 25.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Overall, the fire burned 83,508 acres (33,794 ha; 337.94 km2) of forest, making it the largest wildfire in both South Dakota and Black Hills history.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] It stretched across parts of Custer and Pennington Counties.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The Jasper Fire was 25% larger than any other reported fire in the Black Hills.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Of land use in the Black Hills National Forest, 52,472 acres (21,235 ha) in Hell Canyon Ranger District, 26,294 acres (10,641 ha) in Mystic Ranger District, and 2,836 acres (1,148 ha) of private land burned.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] 27% of the impacted area was so severely burned that all trees were destroyed and ecological succession was reset.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Multiple summer houses and cabins were also destroyed.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Overall, the fire incurred around $9 million in firefighting costs and caused an estimated $42 million in overall damages.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The fire burned 1,279 acres (518 ha), about 90% of the entire area, of Jewel Cave National Monument.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] However, firefighting measures were effective enough that no structures inside the park were lost.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Controlled burns in 1994 and 1999 had cleared away enough underbrush to prevent the fire from moving towards and destroying the visitor center and surrounding buildings.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The Jewel Cave Ranger Station, a historic log cabin, was foamed multiple times to keep it from burning.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The park remained closed until September 2, when the forest was satisfied that the fire was safely contained.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The fire burned much of the natural habitat for various native species, including deer, turkeys, elk, coyotes, porcupines, squirrels, and bobcats.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] However, it increased the natural habitat for insects and woodpeckers, which thrive in snags.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] One pregnant mountain lion that was being tracked by a United States Geological Survey research group was killed in the fire.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Most of the trees lost were ponderosa pines, which are notoriously difficult to regrow in severe burn areas due to their short-distance seed dispersal method.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Additionally, the fire was so intense that it destroyed the seed sources in the soil, leaving no natural way for trees to regenerate inside the burn scar.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The Jasper Fire Area Tree Planting Project began in 2002 with the aim of replacing the thousands of trees lost in the fire and restoring the natural vegetation, using saplings grown in Nebraska's Bessey Nursery.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Under this program, the USFS currently plants about 150,000 new saplings across 400 acres (160 ha) annually within the affected area.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] A 2022 report analyzing vegetation regrowth found that 46% of the most heavily-burned area showed little to no regeneration.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The cause of the fire was quickly determined to be arson.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Two separate witnesses identified Stevenson's car at the fire's point of origin.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Stevenson was arrested at a relative's house in Custer.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] According to her family and her lawyer, Stevenson had a history of mental illness and setting fires.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] During the investigation, Stevenson admitted she could have put out the fire before it spread; she later stated she meant to start the fire but did not think it would grow so large.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] She was also questioned about potential involvement in the 1988 Westberry Trails Fire, an unsolved arson which destroyed 15 homes in Rapid City, South Dakota.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] A polygraph expert said Stevenson admitted to setting three other fires prior to Jasper.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] In May 2001, Stevenson entered a guilty plea agreement, requiring her to plead guilty to arson as well as to cooperate with the Westberry investigation.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] However, after Stevenson failed a polygraph test regarding the Westberry Trails Fire, Assistant Attorney General Paul Bachand sought a harsher sentence—asking 25 years instead of just 17 1/2—and argued that Stevenson had violated the terms of the plea.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Stevenson's attorney opposed the reversal, stating it was motivated by the opportunity to close the Westberry Trails case.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] In July, Stevenson was sentenced to 10 years in prison for destruction of U.S. federal property.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] The following month, she was sentenced to an additional 25 years for second-degree arson, to be served concurrently with the previous 10-year sentence.
[src:dakota-territory/2000-jasper-fire] Stevenson appealed her sentence, but it was upheld by the South Dakota Supreme Court in 2002.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Following the United States Supreme Court's landmark ruling to overturn *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Wade* on June 24, 2022, the state's trigger law, HB 1466, was blocked by the district court, which was upheld by the North Dakota Supreme Court.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] SB 2150 was passed in response to this, making performance of an abortion is a Class C felony subject to a maximum penalty of five years' imprisonment, a $10,000 fine, or both.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2024, Judge Bruce Romanick overturned the state's abortion ban.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In November 2025, the state Supreme Court restored the abortion ban.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] By 1950, the state legislature had passed a law stating that a woman who had an abortion or actively sought to have an abortion regardless of whether she went through with it was guilty of a criminal offense.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] The state was one of 23 states in 2007 to have a detailed abortion-specific informed consent requirement.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] North Dakota's informed consent materials included a definition for fetus stating it is "a Latin word meaning young one or offspring".
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] According to North Dakota's materials, at 10 weeks, the fetus "now has a distinct human appearance" and "eyelids are formed".
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] The materials say at 14 weeks, the fetus "is able to swallow" and "sleeps and awakens".
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] North Dakota's HB 1572, otherwise known as the *Personhood of Children Act*, was a bill in the North Dakota Legislature which aimed to "provide equality and rights to all human beings at every stage of biological development".
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] This step could have eventually eliminated all types of abortion for nearly any reason in the state of North Dakota.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] It would have allocated rights to “the pre-born, partially born”.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] If it had passed, it would have likely been used to challenge *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In March 2013, Governor Jack Dalrymple of North Dakota signed into law a bill presented to him by the legislature that would have banned abortions in the state six weeks after a woman's first missed period (North Dakota HB 1456).
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Only North Dakota successfully passed a such a "fetal heartbeat" law that year, although it was later struck down by the courts.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Dalrymple stated that it was "a legitimate attempt by a state legislature to discover the boundaries of *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2013, state Targeted Regulation of Abortion Providers (TRAP) had provisions related to admitting privileges and licensing.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] They required clinics have hospital privileges.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] The state had a law on the books as of August 2018 that would be triggered if *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] As of mid-May 2019, abortion in North Dakota was banned after week 22.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Abortion in North Dakota remained legal following the United States' Supreme Court ruling to overturn *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] The state has a trigger law from 2007, banning all abortions, which has been blocked by a court since July.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Under the trigger law, performance of an abortion is a Class C felony subject to a maximum penalty of five years' imprisonment, a $10,000 fine, or both.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] A state district court issued a preliminary injunction preventing enforcement of the law while the court is deciding the merits of the case.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] On January 6 2023, Janne Myrdal, Keith Boehm, Larry Luick, Todd Porter (politician), Karen Rohr and Matthew Ruby introduced SB 2150 as an "emergency measure", banning all abortions with exception for health of the pregnant person, and rape or incest when under 6 weeks.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] It became law April 26, 2023 and is the current basis for North Dakota’s abortion ban.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In January 2025, State Representative Lori VanWinkle proposed House Bill 1373, which would have effectively outlawed abortion in all instances by codifying into law the definition of person in relation to murder, assault, and wrongful death as including the unborn child.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Supreme Court's decision in 1973's *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Wade* meant the state could no longer regulate abortion in the first trimester.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] (However, the Supreme Court overturned *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, No.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] 19-1392, 597 U.S. ___ (2022) later in 2022.) In July 2015 the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed a lower court decision blocking HB 1456 (a "fetal heartbeat" law that would ban abortion from six weeks after fertilization) from going into effect.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Supreme Court declined to review the case and the law remains permanently blocked.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In July 2013, a lawsuit was filed with regard to the law by the Center for Reproductive Rights (CRR), on behalf of the only abortion clinic in North Dakota, Red River Women's Clinic.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Circuit Court of Appeals blocked the bill.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Supreme Court, but the court denied a writ of certiorari in January 2015 and let stand the decision of the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Following the 2022 *Dobbs* decision, Burleigh County District Judge Bruce Romanick granted a preliminary injunction on the state's trigger law on abortion, which was upheld by the North Dakota Supreme Court in 2023.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In September 2024, Judge Bruce Romanick struck down the state's new abortion ban, stating that it violated the North Dakota State Constitution.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In January 2025, the North Dakota Supreme Court denied the state government's request to reinstate the total ban.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In November 2025, three of the five justices on the North Dakota Supreme Court ruled that the law was "unconstitutionally vague." However, the North Dakota State Constitution requires that at least four judges join in an opinion to strike down a law, so the ban was allowed to take effect again.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Wade* ruling, two abortion clinics opened in the state, one in Grand Forks and one in Jamestown.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Around 1981, when the doctors in Grand Forks and Jamestown were getting close to an age where they would consider retiring, they reached out to Jane Bovard and asked her to open a clinic in Fargo.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Bovard had a history of supporting abortion rights in the state by assisting women in traveling to Minneapolis or cities in other states to get abortions.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] She agreed and with the help of Susan Hill opened a Women's Health Organization affiliate in the fall of that year.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] From 1981 to 1991, there were three abortion clinics in the state.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 1991, the doctors in Grand Forks and Jamestown both retired, leaving the Women's Health Organization as the only abortion provider in the state.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In the period between 1992 and 1996, the state saw no change in the total number of abortion clinics.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] While only three states saw gains in this period, this state was one of four to see no changes with one abortion clinic in the state in 1996.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] George Miks was the primary physician at the Women's Health Organization in 1993.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Around 1998, he and Jane Bovard felt they could improve on the services offered by the Women's Health Organization so the pair opened a second clinic in the state called the Red River Clinic in Fargo.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Located only six blocks apart, the two clinics were in competition with each other for about two and a half years.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In February 2001, Women's Health Organization closed unexpectedly.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Around 1998, the number of abortions performed at Red River Women's Clinic per week was around 25.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] By 2017, the numbers had dropped slightly to be around 20 to 25 abortions a week.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2008 and 2014, there was still only one abortion clinic in North Dakota.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2014, 98% of the counties in the state did not have an abortion clinic.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] That year, 73% of women in the state aged 15–44 lived in a county without an abortion clinic.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2016, only a small section of the state required women to drive fewer than 40 miles to access an abortion clinic.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2017, there were no Planned Parenthood clinics in the state.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] As of July 21, 2017, North Dakota, Wyoming, Mississippi, Louisiana, Kentucky, and West Virginia were the only six states that did not have a Planned Parenthood clinic offering abortion services.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Of those states, North Dakota and Wyoming were the only two without a Planned Parenthood clinic.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In May 2019, the state was officially one of six in the nation with only one abortion clinic.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2022, anticipating the decision in *Dobbs v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, Red River Women's Clinic chose to relocate.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In the period between 1972 and 1974, there were zero recorded illegal abortion deaths in the state.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 1990, 68,000 women in the state faced the risk of an unintended pregnancy.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] The lowest number of legal induced abortions by state in 2000 occurred in Idaho with 801, while South Dakota was second with 878, and North Dakota was third with 1,341.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Idaho had the fewest induced abortions in 2001 with 738, while South Dakota was second with 895, and North Dakota was third with 1,216.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2003, the state of South Dakota had the lowest number of legal induced abortions with 819.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Idaho was second with 911, while North Dakota was third with 1,354.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2010, the state had no publicly funded abortions.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2014, 47% of adults said in a poll by the Pew Research Center that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] In 2017, the state had an infant mortality rate of 4.3 deaths per 1,000 live births.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Women from the state participated in marches supporting abortion rights as part of a #StoptheBans movement in May 2019.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Wade on June 24, 2022, over 1,000 abortion rights protesters rallied and marched in Fargo, Bismarck and Grand Forks.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Protesters picketed outside the home of Jane Bovard many times.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] She ran a well-known search service that brokered abortions for women who sought them.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] Anti-abortion rights activists threatened Bovard many times, including while outside her home.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-north-dakota] She responded by calling the police; her husband helped protect her by loading his shotgun.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In November 2024, South Dakotans voted on Amendment G, which, if passed, would have amended the state constitution to create a right to abortion in the first two trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The amendment failed by a 41–59% margin.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] By 1950, the state legislature had passed a law stating that a woman who had an abortion or actively sought to have an abortion, regardless of whether she went through with it, was guilty of a criminal offense.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Some states require that a person seeking an abortion must wait for a period of one to six days, depending on the state, after visiting the provider for the first time and before having the procedure.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] South Dakota requires that the patient obtain mandatory counseling from an anti-abortion crisis pregnancy center during this time frame.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 2004, a bill outlawing abortion passed both houses of the legislature, but was vetoed by the Governor due to a technicality.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Wade* in the United States Supreme Court.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] A separate minority report criticizing the process and reaching different conclusions was also released.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The South Dakota legislature passed a law in 2006 that would have banned abortion in the state.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Several members of the South Dakota legislative majority, as well as Governor Rounds, acknowledged that the overt goal of this law, the Women's Health and Human Life Protection Act, was to get the Supreme Court to overturn *Roe.* It was signed into law by Republican Governor Mike Rounds.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Planned Parenthood successfully challenged the law using a ballot initiative instead of using the courts.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In the informed consent materials given to women in Idaho, Oklahoma, South Dakota and Texas required by statute, the materials used graphic and inflammatory language.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The law also required the woman be told how far advanced her pregnancy was.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The informed consent materials in South Dakota, Texas, Utah and West Virginia given to women seeking abortions include counseling materials that say women who have abortions may have suicidal thoughts or they may experience "postabortion traumatic stress syndrome".
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The latter syndrome is not recognized by American Psychological Association or the American Psychiatric Association.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The written informed consent materials in South Dakota say "unborn child may feel physical pain" without specifying any time period during gestation.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Conversely, The *Journal of the American Medical Association* has published notable work indicating that pain sensors do not develop in the fetus until between weeks 23 and 30.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 2008, the South Dakota legislature passed another anti-abortion law, this time one that would have banned abortion in all cases except for rape, incest, and the health of the woman.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Planned Parenthood again successfully challenged this using a ballot initiative instead of using the courts.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 2013, the Targeted Regulation of Abortion Providers (TRAP) state law applied to medication-induced abortions and private doctor offices in addition to abortion clinics.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The state had a law on the books in August 2018 that would be triggered if *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] 19-1392, 597 U.S. ___ (2022) .) As of 2018, South Dakota prohibits the use of state funds for abortions unless the mother's life is in danger.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In mid-May 2019, state law banned abortion after week 22.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] On September 7, 2021, during the COVID-19 pandemic, Governor Kristi Noem signed an executive order requiring in-person medical visits—not merely telehealth appointments—for the prescription of medication abortions.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] A referendum to repeal the Women's Health and Human Life Protection Act was placed on ballot for the November 2006 statewide election due to a successful petition drive by the organization South Dakota Campaign for Healthy Families.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] On May 30, over 38,000 petition signatures were filed, more than twice the 17,000 required to place a measure on the ballot.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] On November 7, WHHLPA was repealed by the South Dakota electorate; the vote was 56%-44% favoring repeal.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 2008, Right to Life of South Dakota gathered enough signatures to put an initiative measure on the ballot.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Initiative Measure 11 would have restricted abortion to cases involving rape, incest, and the woman's health.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] That initiative was defeated, by a vote of 55%-45%.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The US Supreme Court's decision in 1973's *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Wade* ruling meant the state could no longer regulate abortion in the first trimester.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] However, the Supreme Court overturned *Roe v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Rounds* (2012), the United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit ruled that a South Dakota law requiring doctors to give patients information about the potential suicide risk in women who have abortions was not unconstitutional.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 1967, physician Benjamin Munson opened an illegal abortion clinic in Rapid City.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] He was arrested and charged in 1969 for performing an illegal abortion on a 19-year-old woman.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Munson appealed his conviction and won at the circuit court, but after the state appealed the decision, the South Dakota Supreme Court ruled against him.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Wade* decision rendered his further appeals moot.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Buck Williams started offering abortion services at his Sioux Falls clinic.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] At the time, he was the only abortion service provider in the state.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 1989, he approached Planned Parenthood about taking over his clinic.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] At the time, Planned Parenthood had no operations in South Dakota.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] They agreed, and have been the state's only abortion service provider ever since.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Planned Parenthood moved out of their old building, and the building was taken over by AlphaCenter and run by Leslee Unruh.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Another clinic had opened in the stated by 1982 but was closed by 1992.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] While only three states saw gains in this period, this state was one of four to see no changes, with one abortion clinic in the state in 1996.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 2014, there was one abortion clinic in the state.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] That year, 77% of women in the state aged 15–44 lived in a county without an abortion clinic.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 2017, there was one Planned Parenthood clinic, which offered abortion services, in a state with a population of 181,145 women aged 15–49.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The Planned Parenthood facility was the only one providing abortion services in the state.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Unable to find local doctors to run the clinic, they hired four doctors who flew in from out of state to work on rotation.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Planned Parenthood stopped offering abortion services in the state after the *Dobbs v.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Jackson Women's Health Organization* decision.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 1990, 72,000 women in the state faced the risk of an unintended pregnancy.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 2013, among white women aged 15–19, there were 70 abortions, 10 abortions for black women aged 15–19, 0 abortions for Hispanic women aged 15–19, and 10 abortions for women of all other races.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 2014, 48% of adults said in a poll by the Pew Research Center that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In 2017, the state had an infant mortality rate of 7.7 deaths per 1,000 live births.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Wade* on June 24, 2022, six people were arrested on June 29 following an abortion rights protest in Sioux Falls.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] On July 9–10, hundreds of abortion rights protesters rallied and marched in Sioux Falls and Rapid City.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] On July 23, about 100 abortion rights protesters rallied and marched at the South Dakota State Capitol in Pierre.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Abortion rights protests were also held at the University of South Dakota in Vermillion.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] On May 1, 2024, Dakotans For Health submitted a petition with over 55,000 signatures to get abortion rights on the ballot in the November 2024 election, more than the 35,000 signatures required.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] The proposed amendment to the state constitution would legalize abortion in the first trimester.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] Alpha Center is a crisis pregnancy center based in Sioux Falls and run by Leslee Unruh.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] In October 1999, Martin Uphoff set fire to a Planned Parenthood clinic in Sioux Falls, causing $100 worth of damage.
[src:dakota-territory/abortion-in-south-dakota] He was later sentenced to 60 months in prison.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The **Territory of Dakota** was an organized incorporated territory of the United States that existed from March 2, 1861, until November 2, 1889, when the final extent of the reduced territory was split and admitted to the Union as the states of North and South Dakota.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The Dakota Territory consisted of the northernmost part of the land acquired in the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, as well as the southernmost part of Rupert's Land, which was acquired in 1818 when the boundary was changed to the 49th parallel.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The name refers to the Dakota branch of the Sioux tribes which occupied the area at the time.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Most of Dakota Territory was formerly part of the Minnesota and Nebraska territories.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] When Minnesota became a state in 1858, the leftover area between the Missouri River and Minnesota's western boundary fell unorganized.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] When the Yankton Treaty was signed later that year, ceding much of what had been Sioux Indian land to the U.S.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Government, early settlers formed a provisional government and unsuccessfully lobbied for United States territory status.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Wilmot Wood Brookings was the provisional governor.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The cities of Wilmot and Brookings as well as Brookings County are named for him.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Three years later, President-elect Abraham Lincoln's cousin-in-law John Blair Smith Todd personally lobbied for territory status, and the U.S.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Congress formally created Dakota Territory.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] It became an organized territory on March 2, 1861.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Upon creation, Dakota Territory included much of present-day Montana and Wyoming as well as all of present-day North Dakota and South Dakota and a small portion of present-day Nebraska.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] President Lincoln appointed Dakota Territory's first governor, William Jayne, who was Lincoln's old friend and neighbor from Springfield, Illinois.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] A small patch of land known as "Lost Dakota" existed as a remote exclave of Dakota Territory until it became part of Gallatin County, Montana Territory, in 1873.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] All land north of the Keya Paha River (which includes most of Boyd County, Nebraska, and a smaller portion of neighboring Keya Paha County) was originally part of Dakota Territory, but was transferred to Nebraska in 1882.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Dakota Territory was not directly involved in the American Civil War but did raise some troops to defend the settlements following the Dakota War of 1862 which triggered hostilities with the Sioux tribes of Dakota Territory.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The Department of the Northwest sent expeditions into Dakota Territory in 1863, 1864 and 1865.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] It also established forts in Dakota Territory to protect the frontier settlements of the Territory, Iowa and Minnesota and the traffic along the Missouri River.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Following the Civil War, hostilities continued with the Sioux until the 1868 Treaty of Fort Laramie.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] By 1868, creation of new territories reduced Dakota Territory to the present boundaries of the Dakotas.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Territorial counties were defined in 1872, including Bottineau County, Cass County and others.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] During the existence of the organized territory, the population first increased very slowly and then very rapidly with the "Dakota Boom" from 1870 to 1880.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Because the Sioux were considered very hostile and a threat to early settlers, the white population grew slowly.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Gradually, the settlers' population grew and the Sioux were not considered as severe a threat.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The population increase can largely be attributed to the growth of the Northern Pacific Railroad.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Settlers who came to the Dakota Territory were from other western territories as well as many from northern and western Europe.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] These included large numbers of Norwegians, Germans, Swedes, and Canadians.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Commerce was originally organized around the fur trade.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Furs were carried by steamboat along the rivers to the settlements.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Gold was discovered in the Black Hills in 1874 and attracted more settlers, setting off the last Sioux War.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The population surge increased the demand for meat spurring expanded cattle ranching on the territory's vast open ranges.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] With the advent of the railroad agriculture intensified: wheat became the territory's main cash crop.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Economic hardship hit the territory in the 1880s due to lower wheat prices and a drought.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] There are two conflicting narratives on why the Dakota Territory was divided and given statehood.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] One narrative suggests that it was due to regionalist tensions while the other suggests that it was a political play by Gilded Age Republicans.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Regionalist tensions between the northern and the southern parts of the territory were present since the beginning.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The southern part was always more populated, in the 1880 Census, the southern part had a population of 98,268, two and a half times the northern part's 36,909.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The southern part also considered the north to be somewhat disreputable, "too much controlled by the wild folks, cattle ranchers, fur traders” and too frequently the site of conflict with the indigenous population.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The railroad also connected the northern and southern parts to different hubs – the northern part, via Fargo and Bismarck became closer tied to the Minneapolis–Saint Paul area, while the southern part became closer tied to Sioux City and from there to Omaha.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Politically, territorial legislators were appointed by the federal government, and tended to remain in the region only while they served their terms.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The larger population of the southern region began to resent them, while the northerners tended to emphasize that it was cheaper to be a territory, with the federal government funding a wide range of state functions.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Ordway moved the territorial capital from Yankton to Bismarck in 1883.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The capital grab, which moved the capital away from the majority of the population fueled more resentment from the south.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The southern part was anxious for statehood so they could have their own capital.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] They had already crossed the 60,000 population necessary for statehood; so, they held a convention in September of 1883, drafted a state constitution, and submitted it to the voters.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] It was approved by the electors and submitted to Congress.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] A bill providing for statehood of the Dakota Territory south of the 46th parallel of latitude was passed by the Senate in December 1884, but failed to pass the House.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] A second constitutional convention for South Dakota was held in September 1885, framing a new constitution and submitted it to the vote of the people, who ratified it with an overwhelming vote.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Conventions favoring division of Dakota into two states were also held in the northern section, one in 1887 at Fargo, and another in 1888, at Jamestown.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Both adopted provisions memorializing Congress to divide the territory and admit both North and South Dakota as states.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Various bills were introduced in Congress on the matter; one in 1885 to admit South Dakota as a state, and organize the northern half as Lincoln Territory.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Another bill introduced in 1886, proposed to admit the entire Territory as a single state.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Still another provided for all of the Territory east of the Missouri River to become a single state, the balance to be organized as Lincoln or North Dakota Territory.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Other bills were introduced in 1887 and 1888, but failed to pass.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The Territorial Legislature of 1887 submitted the question of division to a popular vote at the general election of November 1887.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] When full returns of this election finally came in on January 10, 1888, 37,784 favored division and 32,913 were opposed.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] In 1889, Republican Benjamin Harrison became president of the United States and favoured statehood for Dakota.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] In order to become a state, a territory was required to have a population of at least 60,000.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] In 1889, southern Dakota had a population of over 340,000, and northern Dakota had a population of over 150,000 so Congress is said to have decided that it was finally time to grant statehood.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] But in reality, the Republican Party, which wanted more power in the U.S.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Senate, put on pressure to divide Dakota into two states.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] With two senators from each state, the Republicans would gain four more senate seats in Congress.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] After defeating Democratic President Grover Cleveland in the 1888 election, they celebrated by splitting the Republican-dominated Dakota into two territories and admitting *both* of them as states.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Today, there are still two Dakotas because Gilded Age Republicans wanted four senators instead of just two.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] In their eagerness to admit both Dakotas, congressmen also ignored that much of the land in the anticipated state of South Dakota belonged to the Sioux.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Yankton's status as an important port was literally crushed on March 27, 1881, when an ice dam on the Missouri River burst, sending flood waters and giant blocks of ice flowing towards the town.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The resulting flood waters continued to accumulate behind the debris, and by March 29, the town's riverfront and downtown were covered in water, ice and rock, destroying or stranding several riverboats that were moored there.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] As a result of this flood, and the expansion of railroads as a preferred method of shipping goods, Yankton's river boat traffic was reduced, and the city's role as a prominent stopping point on the way west dwindled over the next several years.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] It was also not especially unusual for the party that controls Congress to admit states for political reasons.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] In 1864, Republican President Abraham Lincoln signed legislation admitting Nevada, a barely populated desert state with a few thousand residents, into the union as a state.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The few people who did live there were overwhelmingly Republican.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] A dozen years later, President Ulysses Grant, also a Republican, signed legislation admitting Republican-dominated Colorado as a state even though according to the then latest census, Colorado had fewer than 40,000 residents.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Republicans also successfully blocked New Mexico from becoming a state until 1912 while Cleveland’s Democrats had hoped to admit New Mexico as it would have favored them.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The admission of new western states was a party political battleground, with each party looking at how the proposed new states were likely to vote.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] At the beginning of 1888, the Democrats under president Grover Cleveland proposed that the four territories of Montana, New Mexico, Dakota and Washington should be admitted together.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The first two were expected to vote Democratic and the latter two were expected to vote Republican so this was seen as a compromise acceptable to both parties.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] However, the Republicans won majorities in both the House and the Senate later that year.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] To head off the possibility that Congress might only admit Republican territories to statehood, the Democrats agreed to a less favorable deal in which Dakota was divided in two and New Mexico was left out altogether.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Cleveland signed it into law on February 22, 1889, and the territories could become states nine months after that.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] There had been previous attempts to open up the territory, but these had foundered because the Treaty of Fort Laramie (1868) required that 75 percent of Sioux adult males on the reservation had to agree to any treaty change.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Most recently, a commission headed by Richard Henry Pratt in 1888 had completely failed to get the necessary signatures in the face of opposition from Sioux leaders and even government worker Elaine Goodale, later Superintendent of Indian Education for the Dakotas.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The government believed that the Dawes Act (1887), which attempted to move the Indians from hunting to farming, in theory, meant that they needed less land (but in reality was an economic disaster for them) and that at least half was available for sale.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Congress approved an offer of $1.25 per acre ($3.1/ha) for reservation land (a figure they had previously rejected as outrageously high) and $25,000 to induce the Indians to sign.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] A new commission was appointed in April 1889 that included veteran Indian fighter general George Crook.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Crook pulled out all the stops to get the Indians to sign, using many underhand tactics.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] He threatened them that if they did not sign, the land would be taken anyway and they would get nothing.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] This would not have been seen as an idle threat; the treaty had been ignored in the past when the Black Hills were taken from the Sioux.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Crook ignored leaders like Sitting Bull and Red Cloud who opposed the sale and kept them out of the negotiations, preferring instead to deal with moderate leaders like American Horse.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] American Horse, however, claimed immediately afterwards that he had been tricked into signing.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Crook made many personal promises (such as on reservation rations) which he had no authority to make, or ability to keep.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] He claimed afterwards that he had only agreed to report the concerns back to Washington.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Crook lied about how many signatures he already had, giving the impression that the signature he was currently asking for would make no difference.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] He said that those who did not sign would not get a share of the money for the land.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Crook even allowed white men who had married Sioux to sign, a dubious action given that the blood quantum laws only counted full-blood Indians as members of the tribe.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] By August 6, 1889, Crook had the requisite number of signatures, half the reservation land was sold, and the remainder divided among six smaller reservations.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] On February 22, 1889, outgoing President Cleveland signed an omnibus bill that divided the Territory of Dakota in half.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] North Dakota and South Dakota became states simultaneously on November 2, 1889.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] President Harrison had the papers shuffled to obscure which one was signed first and the order went unrecorded.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The bill also enabled the people in the new Territories of North Dakota and South Dakota, as well as the older territories of Montana and Washington, to write state constitutions and elect state governments.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] The four new states would be admitted into the Union in nine months.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] This plan cut Democratic New Mexico out of statehood and split Republican Dakota Territory into two new Republican states.
[src:dakota-territory/dakota-territory] Rather than two new Republican states and two new Democratic states that Congress had considered the previous year, the omnibus bill created three new Republican states and one new Democratic state that Republicans thought they would capture.
